examine_outcome_variables <- function() {

# A note on roles:
# All profile_level outcome variables, by definition, imply that an actor was involved in the knowledge flow process.
# As described in more detail in the operationalization section, three key roles are used to classify the nature of the interaction
# of each actor with each flow of knowledge, as follows:
#   1) reporter: 	The reporter actor is the one who first releases the "problem knowledge" by creating and filing a bug report
#   2) assigned_to: The assigned_to actor is the one who is put in charge of creating the "solution knowledge" by resolving the problems revealed in the bug report
#   3) qa_contact:	The qa_contact actor is the one who is put in charge of verifying that the "solution knowledge" actually solves the "problem"
#
# These three roles are inherent in the structure of the Mozilla database.  Every "problem knowledge" will have a "reporter" actor and, hence, associated organization
# (see org-level analysis).  All releases of "solution knowledge" should have an "assigned_to" actor and associated organization.  Only a select few bugs
# have an associated "qa_contact" actor because, most often, it is a role is only filled when a bug (problem knowledge) is sufficiently complex that it is difficult
# to assess at face value if a given solution solves the problem.  The distribution of roles at the bug-level is as follows:
#   Total bugs: 													n = 774,765 (100.000%)
#     Bugs with (valid) reporter actor:								n = 774,744 ( 99.997%)
#     Bugs with (valid) assigned_to actor:							n = 504,990 ( 65.180%)
#	  Bugs with (valid) qa_contact actor:							n = 265,588 ( 34.280%)
# 	  Bugs with (valid) assigned_to & qa_contact actors: 			n = 253,993 ( 32.783%)
# 	  Bugs with (valid) reporter, assigned_to & qa_contact actors: 	n = 253,992 ( 32.783%)

# As a result of the role distinction at the profile-level, in line with the research question, it is necessary to aggregate
# the bug level to the profile level according to role.  Said another way, each individual actor will influence the bug-level outcome variables as
# some combination of reporter, assigned_to, or qa_contact actor.  Those invidual actors who never take on one of these three roles
# have moderating effects on other actor-bug knowledge flows, but are not one of the primary participants in the knowledge-flow activity (as operationalized).
# This operationalization decision was made based on the limitations of the dtabase structure and represents a conservative subset of the primary
# actors involved in the knowlege-flow process as defined by the problem knowledge releases to solution knowledge emergence nature of the research question.
# The moderating effects influenced by secondary actors in aggregate are represented as independent variables.

# In summary, in order to represent the outcome variables at the profile-level, each outcome is distinguished by the role the individual actor played
# in the knowledge flow process of the bugs whose variables are aggregated to create the profile-level outcome variables: reporter, assigned_to, qa_contact.
