# Revisiting the nature of the original percent fixed | fixed with at least one patch data, we note that given that it is percent-based data, that it
# necessarily assumes values in the standard unit interval (0,1).  As a result, it is unsurprising that the data clusters around 0% and 100%.
# Data of this nature is well suited to a novel form of analysis known as Beta Regression (Cribari-Neto & Zeileis, 2010; Grün, Kosmidis, and Zeileis, 2012) built upon classic binomial probability statistical analysis principles (Williams, 1982; Prentice, 1986).
# The analysis assumes that the dependent variable (percent fixed in our case) is beta-distributed, accounting for the heteroskedasticity & kurtosis inherent in standard unit interval data (as we observed in the graphs)
# This approach has been found to be superior to log or power based transformations of the dependent variable  as it improves interpretability and accounts for non-Gaussian asymmetry (Ferrari & Cribari-Neto, 2004).
# Further, it promotes data-driven statistical analysis rather than forcing standard tests to fit non-ideal data (Cribari-Neto & Zeileis, 2010)

# In conclusion, we select beta regression for the percent_bugs_reported_fixed | fixed_at_least_one_patch dependent variables
# We use the up-to-date statistical analysis package "betareg" in R, developed by Simas & Rocha (2006) and updated by Zeileis, et al. (2014)
# Details provided here: https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/betareg/vignettes/betareg.pdf & https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/betareg/
# Further details: Cribari-Neto & Zeileis (2010). Beta Regression in R. Journal of Statistical Software 34(2), 1-24. URL http://www.jstatsoft.org/v34/i02/.
# And: Gruen, Kosmidis, & Zeileis (2012). Extended Beta Regression in R: Shaken, Stirred, Mixed, and Partitioned. Journal of Statistical Software, 48(11), 1-25. URL http://www.jstatsoft.org/v48/i11/.



# Time to outcome tendencies

# In this section, we consider the class of outcome variables related to time to outcome.
# There are three variables of interest, as follows:
#	1) days_to_resolution_mean: 						This variable is collected as continuous and measures the time between bug creation (creation_ts) and bug resolution (censor_ts).
#									  					  It is independent of the actual resolution (could be fixed or not_fixed) which is handled above.
#	2) days_to_first_assignment_mean:					This variable is collected as continuous and measures the time between bug creation (creation_ts) and first assignment to be worked on.  Its purpose is to
#									  					  account for the delay in starting work on a given bug.  It is necessarily shorter than days_to_resolution.  However, many bugs go straight to resolution
#									  					  and are never assigned at all.  As such its n is much lower than days_to_resolution.
#   3) days_from_first_assignment_to_resolution_mean: 	This variable is collected as continuous and should, in theory be the difference between variables 1) & 2).  However, in practice, it often varies, reflecting
#														  the fact that some bugs need to be reopened, redeveloped, bounced, and so on, all of which are captured in this variable.
